# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-doolittle-walcott
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] In the United States, an **act of Congress** is a statute passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives of the United States Congress and signed into law by the president.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Acts may apply only to individual entities (called private laws), or to the general public (public laws).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] In the United States, acts of Congress are designated as either **public laws**, relating to the general public, or **private laws**, relating to specific institutions or individuals.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Since 1957, all acts of Congress have been designated as "Public Law X–Y" or "Private Law X–Y".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] X is the number of the Congress and Y refers to the sequential order of the bill (when it was enacted).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] 111–5 (American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009) was the fifth enacted public law of the 111th United States Congress.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Public laws are also often abbreviated as Pub.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] When the legislation of those two kinds are proposed, it is called public bill and private bill respectively.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The word "act", as used in the term "act of Congress", is a common, not a proper noun.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The capitalization of the word "act" (especially when used standing alone to refer to an act mentioned earlier by its full name) is deprecated by some dictionaries and usage authorities.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] However, the Bluebook requires "Act" to be capitalized when referring to a specific legislative act.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The United States Code capitalizes "act".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The term "act of Congress" is sometimes used in informal speech to indicate something for which getting permission is burdensome.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Reconsideration by the Congress after a presidential veto during its session.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] A bill must receive a 2⁄3 majority vote in both houses to override a president's veto.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The president promulgates acts of Congress made by the first two methods.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] If an act is made by the third method, the presiding officer of the house that last reconsidered the act promulgates it.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Under the United States Constitution, if the president does not return a bill or resolution to Congress with objections before the time limit expires, then the bill automatically becomes an act.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] If the Congress is adjourned at the end of this period, then the bill dies and cannot be reconsidered (see pocket veto).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] If the president rejects a bill or resolution while the Congress is in session, a two-thirds vote of both houses of Congress is needed for reconsideration to be successful.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Promulgation in the sense of publishing and proclaiming the law is accomplished by the president, or the relevant presiding officer in the case of an overridden veto, delivering the act to the archivist of the United States.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] The archivist provides for its publication as a slip law and in the United States Statutes at Large after receiving the act.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Thereafter, the changes are published in the United States Code.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] Through the process of judicial review, an act of Congress that violates the Constitution may be declared unconstitutional by the courts.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] A judicial declaration that an act of Congress is unconstitutional does not remove the act from the Statutes at Large or the United States Code; rather, it prevents the act from being enforced.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/act-of-congress] However, the act as published in annotated codes and legal databases is marked with annotations indicating that it is no longer good law.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Charles Doolittle Walcott was born on March 31, 1850, in New York Mills, New York.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott, moved from Rhode Island in 1822.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] His father, also Charles Doolittle Walcott, died when Charles Jr. was only two.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott was the youngest of four children.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He was interested in nature from an early age, collecting minerals and bird eggs and, eventually, fossils.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He attended various schools in the Utica area but left at the age of eighteen without completing high school, the end of his formal education.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] His interest in fossils solidified as he became a commercial fossil collector.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] On January 9, 1872, Walcott married Lura Ann Rust, daughter of the owner of a farm in New York where Walcott made one of his most important trilobite discoveries (Walcott-Rust quarry).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott's interest in fossils led to his acquaintance with Louis Agassiz of Harvard University, who encouraged him to work in the field of paleontology; later that year, he began work as the assistant to the state paleontologist, James Hall.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He lost this job after two years but was soon recruited to the newly formed US Geological Survey as a geological assistant.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott began his professional paleontology career by discovering new localities, such as the Walcott-Rust quarry in upstate New York and the Georgia Plane trilobite beds in Vermont, and by selling specimens to Yale University.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1876, he became the assistant to James Hall, State Geologist of New York.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott also became a member of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1879, Walcott joined the US Geological Survey and rose to become chief paleologist in 1893 and then director in 1894.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] His work focused on Cambrian strata in locations throughout the United States and Canada; his numerous field trips and fossil discoveries made important contributions to stratigraphy.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He married Helena Breese Stevens in 1888.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] They had four children between 1889 and 1896: Charles Doolittle Walcott, Sydney Stevens Walcott, Helena Breese Walcott, and Benjamin Stuart Walcott.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1896, the American Philosophical Society in 1897, and the American Academy of Art and Sciences in 1899.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1901, he served both as president of the Geological Society of America and the Philosophical Society of Washington.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1902, he met with Andrew Carnegie and became one of the founders and incorporators of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He served in various administrative and research positions in that organization.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1921 Walcott was awarded the inaugural Mary Clark Thompson Medal from the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He served as president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1923.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Geological Survey under President Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott had an interest in the conservation movement and assisted its efforts.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott became Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution in 1907 after the death of Samuel Pierpont Langley, holding the post until his own death.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] He was succeeded by Charles Greeley Abbot.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Because of Walcott's responsibilities at the Smithsonian, he resigned as director of the United States Geological Survey.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] As part of the centennial celebration of Darwin's birth, Walcott was awarded an honorary doctorate by the University of Cambridge in 1909.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1910, the year after his discovery of 505 million year old (middle Cambrian) fossils in the Burgess shale, Walcott returned to the area accompanied by his sons Stuart and Sidney.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Together they examined all the layers on the ridge above the point where the fossil-laden rock had been found, eventually finding the fossiliferous band.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Between 1910 and 1924, Walcott returned repeatedly to collect more than 65,000 specimens from what is now known as the Walcott Quarry, named after him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] The find includes exceptional preservation of the soft parts of its fossils, one of the oldest fossil beds containing soft-part imprints.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott's wife Helena died in a train crash in Connecticut in 1911.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1914, Walcott married his third wife, Mary Morris Vaux, an amateur artist and avid naturalist.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] She accompanied him on his expeditions, enjoying the study of nature.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] She made watercolor illustrations of wildflowers as she traveled with him in Canada.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Although Walcott spent a considerable amount of time at the Burgess Shale quarry on what became known as Fossil Ridge, he also traveled widely in other areas of the Canadian Rockies.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Some of his numerous scientific publications feature spectacular panoramic photographs of the mountains taken from high passes or high on mountain slopes.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In 1914 Walcott convened a conference in Washington, D.C. for the purpose of stimulating interest in aeronautic science, and its relation to the U.S. government.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Five additional members were chosen "who shall be acquainted with the needs of aeronautical science, either civil or military, or skilled in aeronautical engineering or its allied sciences".
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Scriven, Chief Signal Officer of the Army, was chairman of the committee; Walcott was elected chairman of the Executive Committee.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Durand was one of the civilian members of the Committee.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In light of the Wright brothers patent war and to discredit the Wright brothers, Glenn Curtiss in 1914 helped Walcott secretly make major modifications to a failed aerodrome built in 1903 by Professor Samuel Langley to make it appear able to fly.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] After the flight demonstrations, Walcott ordered the Langley machine be restored to its 1903 condition to cover up the deception before it was put on display.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] After Walcott's death in Washington, D.C., his samples, photographs, and notes remained in storage until their rediscovery by a new generation of paleontologists in the late 1960s.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Since then, many of his interpretations have been revised.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott would be little known today if he had not been brought to attention by Stephen Jay Gould's book *Wonderful Life* (1989).
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] In this book, Gould put forth his opinion that Walcott failed to see the differences among the Burgess Shale species and "shoehorned" most of these fossils into existing phyla.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Many paleontologists would now take a much less negative view of Walcott's descriptions and of the theoretical perspective that shaped them.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] Walcott's work on Ordovician trilobites of New York also tended to be overlooked until, in the early 1990s, Rochester-based amateur paleontologist Thomas Whiteley revived Walcott's research and re-opened the Walcott–Rust quarry near Russia, New York.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] This localized stratum has some of the best preserved Laurentian trilobites ever found, including enrolled specimens with soft body parts.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] The Walcott Peak, near where he first discovered the Burgess Shale on Mount Burgess in Canada, was named after him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] The nearby Walcott Quarry, with the Phyllopod bed of Burgess Shale fossils between Wapta Mountain and Mount Field, is also named for him.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] The Charles Doolittle Walcott Medal is awarded by the National Academy of Sciences every five years for outstanding work in the field of Precambrian and Cambrian life and history.
[src:charles-doolittle-walcott/charles-doolittle-walcott] The World War II Liberty Ship SS *Charles D.
